<div id="Idea_4156"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4156-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4156">Domestic Oil Production/Refinement Domain of the US Federal Government&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/9774-4049">kdtroxel</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">22 hours ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">21.	Domestic Oil Production and Refinement will be the Domain of the United States Federal Government:  Carbon fuels are the lifeblood that drives the daily lives of every American.  With this thought in mind, the procurement and refining of oil, coal, and natural gas should be prioritized as the domain of the public, so long as development is within the boarders of the United States.  Private enterprise should not benefit from this fundamental cost to our society. In essence, this bill nationalizes the oil procurement and refinement within the boundaries of the United States.  The United States government may allow private industry to remain in place as its agents of oil extraction and refinement, but said companies will operate on fixed and variable budgets, meaning salaries and wages will be maintained, capped, and controlled by the federal government. <br/>•	<br/>Investment requests for new sources of oil, coal, solar, wind, or nuclear may be submitted by the agent to the energy subcommittee of congress for approval. Any congressman who serves on the Energy Committee must undergo an extensive training program in the areas of Energy extraction and creation, before being certified/qualified to serve on said committee.  Weekly reports by the Energy Committee must be submitted to the public for debate/discussion/disclosure.  Reports may include the state of energy consumption estimates, procurement estimates, investment requests and plans. Any excess of earnings will remain the property of the federal government and used exclusively to paying off of the principle of the national debt; not part of the general operating fund.  <br/>•	<br/>Suggest creation of an opposite organization, which would validate the agents of energy procurement, and inspect/report on the state of our aging energy facilities.  Expert advisory committee. Such committees in the past have fallen victim to the lure of kickbacks from the industry they are meant to watchdog.  Regular and repeated audits and examinations of this committe has to be inforced.<br/>•	<br/>An alternative to domestic domain of oil extraction and refinement would be to mandate that all future new energy resource extraction and new refinement facilities would become the domain of the Federal Government, where profits from such enterprises become part of the federal general fund. <br/>•	<br/>The problem with private resource development is that the free market often determines the end user.  Meaning, private domestic oil extraction companies will seek to maximize profits by selling oil to whoever pays the most.  Hence, public funds to help establish domestic resource extraction may benefit other countries and not only our own.<br/>•	<br/>If the United States prioritizes domestic resource extractions and/or refinement, then the prices can be adjusted to a variable fixed price, undermining the world market and lessoning our dependence on foreign oil.  So long as said resource is sold solely within the United States.  Government controlled resources should not be sold to foreign governments to reduce trade imbalances.<br/></div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_4156" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_4156', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2255&topicID=4156')">Comments (2)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_4156"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2255">Uncategorized</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=carbon fuel domain">carbon fuel domain</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_4156"></div>
</div></td>
