<td valign="top" style="padding-right:30px; padding-left:20px;">
<div id="Idea_4056"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4056-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4056">Applying sustainable cemetery management techniques to all federally owned cemeteries&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/9311-4049">cabeal1</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">1 day ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent"><br/>THE CATEGORY I WOULD HAVE USED:<br/>PUBLIC ASSET MANAGEMENT or<br/>TRENDSETTING<br/><br/>Current conventional cemetery management consumes a lot of resources: water, herbicide, fertilizer, fuel for mowing, infrastructure, electricity, etc. <br/><br/>The UK, under the guidance of cemeterian Ken West (a UK public employee), began an appeal to the government to manage cemetery land sustainably. His logic was heard, a number of municipal cemeteries began to convert to sustainable cemetery maintenance techniques,and a movement began. The process resulted in lower maintenance costs for the cemeteries, an increase in inner-city habitat and greenspace, and the public's imagination has been captured.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_4056" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_4056', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2255&topicID=4056')">Comments (0)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_4056"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2255">Uncategorized</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=end-of-life care">end-of-life care</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=funerals">funerals</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=burial">burial</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_4056"></div>
</div></td>
</tr>
</table>

